<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-420-308  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 420 308.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 30 1990 v9 n9 p81(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ADP initiatives are a priority in war against drugs. (automateddata processing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Narcotics, Control ofData ProcessingAutomationData AnalysisElectronic Data ProcessingData BasesInformation Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ADP Initiatives Are a Priority in War Against DrugsandM;President Bush has given ADP initiatives high priority in his drugeradication plans.andM;The president's 1990 National Drug Control Strategy report, released inJanuary, calls for the Justice Department to develop a National DrugInformation Center.andP;  The NDIC would combine data gathered by manydrug-related intelligence efforts across government.andP;  The president'sstrategy also outlines goals to improve the automated tools used by the lawenforcement agencies involved in the federal war on drugs.andM;The administration earmarked $10.6 billion for antidrug activities in itsfiscal 1991 budget request.andP;  In the interdiction area, where most ADPinitiatives fall, the president's budget proposes $2.4 billion for enhancingand integrating existing systems.andM;Although the drug control strategy report offered only sketchy details aboutthe planned ADP initiatives, it singled out the El Paso Intelligence Center(EPIC) as the key element in the NDIC.andM;EPIC, a command, control and communications center run by the DrugEnforcement Administration (DEA), is the central repository for federal druginterdiction information.andM;The NDIC will combine the EPIC database with data gathered by other drugenforcement agencies such as the FBI's National Crime Information Center, theJustice Department Computer Center, the Custom Service's command, control,communications and intelligence centers and the Coast Guard.andM;NDIC &quot;will consolidate and coordinate all relevant intelligence gathered bylaw enforcement agencies and analyze it to produce a more complete picture ofdrug-trafficking organizations,&quot; the report said.andM;The report also cites the crucial need for the man y federal agenciesinvolved in drug eradication efforts to enhance their ADP capabilities.andM;&quot;The extent to which drug-related intelligence information can be rapidlydisseminated and cross-referenced through computer database systems iscritical to the success of drug enforcement,&quot; the report said.andP;  &quot;Ifinformation regarding drug-trafficking organizations or individual drugoffenders is available only on paper, inaccessible to agencies that may bepursuing related intelligence, its value is severely limited.&quot;andM;The underpinnings for most automation efforts exist now, the report said, butsome systems need enhancement.andP;  The report cited the Treasury EnforcementCommunications System, the FBI's Drug Information System, EPIC and generalDEA report filing systems as needing upgrades.andM;The report also called for agencies to look to one another for help.andM;&quot;Many of the agencies, particularly the Defense Department, have developedapproaches and methodologies which can be applied with little expense tocorrect the shortfalls of other agencies,&quot; it said.andP;  DOD officials also havepromised to provide technical support to the civilian agency efforts, thereport said.andM;On the research end, the report said the agencies fighting drugs must wedadvanced inspection technologies with computer-generated targeting techniquesand state-of-the-art telecommunications.andO;</TEXT></DOC>